><td><p>14</p></td><td><p>*</p></td><td><p>*</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>In line with standard departmental practice in statistics, we do not publish details of numbers less than 5 as this would breach data protection obligations. Therefore all records of less than 5 have been annotated with an asterisk (*).</p><p> </p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-03-01T17:49:37.423Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694290/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694290/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694290/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-02-24","Jobcentres: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many staff of each grade and gender were employed at (a) Cardiff and (b) Penarth Jobcentre in each of the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Stephen Doughty","Cardiff South and Penarth","Stephen Doughty","65505"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694291","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-03-06","<p>DWP’s diversity statistics are published on the gov.uk website at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/dwp-equality-information-2016-employee-data" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/dwp-equality-information-2016-employee-data</a></p><p> </p><p>Information about the socio-economic background of staff in the Department is not held centrally and is therefore not available.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-03-06T17:54:04.33Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694291/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694291/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694291/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-02-24","Department for Work and Pensions: Senior Civil Servants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what proportion of senior civil servants of his Department are (a) men, (b) women, (c) disabled, (d) from working-class backgrounds and (e) from black, Asian and minority ethnic backgrounds.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","65569"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694292","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-03-02","<p>Claimants to Personal Independence Payment (PIP) who cannot engage effectively with the claims process due to a lack of mental capacity or insight, and who do not have any support from another person or organisation, are considered to require additional support from the DWP and elements of the PIP claims process have been adapted to provide further support for this group.</p><p> </p><p>The PIP Assessment Guide provides guidance for Health Professionals carrying out assessments for PIP on who is likely to require additional support and describes the broad health conditions which would give rise to a lack of mental capacity or insight together with some specific examples. The guidance would not preclude someone with a brain tumour from being considered for additional support if the tumour gave rise to a lack of mental incapacity or insight.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-03-02T15:14:37.107Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694292/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694292/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694292/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-02-24","Personal Independence Payment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, for what reasons brain tumours are not included in the list of health conditions requiring additional support needs in the most recent Personal Independence Payment Assessment guide.","false","Biography information for Martyn Day","Linlithgow and East Falkirk","Martyn Day","65538"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694293","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-03-01","<p>The falling claimant count and the increased use of our online services in recent years mean that 20% of rent is going toward space we are not using. In response, we have sought to redesign our estate in a way that delivers value for the taxpayer while continuing to deliver vital support to our claimants. Many of our offices across Liverpool are currently underutilised, meaning that we are spending money on rent for space that is unused rather than on services and support. The proposal would see a reduction in the number of sites, from 14 Jobcentres to 10 Jobcentres resulting in a space utilisation improvement from 66% to 95%. Merging our staff and services offers the opportunity to maintain and improve the services we provide to claimants across Liverpool while offering the best value for money for the taxpayer.</p><p> </p><p>With 19 front of house and 16 back of house full time equivalent staff occupying 820 m2 of space, utilisation is currently 53% at Wavertree Jobcentre.</p><p> </p><p>With 82 front of house and 9 back of house full time equivalent staff occupying 2,307 m2 space, utilisation is currently 60% at Edge Hill Jobcentre.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-03-01T17:03:25.197Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694293/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694293/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694293/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-02-24","Jobcentres: Liverpool","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, with reference to the oral contribution of 20 February 2017, Official Report, column 768, what the evidential basis is for his statement that the proposals for jobcentres will raise utilisation across the city of Liverpool from 66 per cent to 95 per cent; and what the current utilisation rate is of the jobcentres in (a) Wavertree and (b) Edge Hill.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","65524"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694294","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-03-01","<p>Please see table below for the response from The Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy for the proportion of SCS based on the above questions:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>A) Men</p></td><td><p>56%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>B) Women</p></td><td><p>44%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>C) Disabled</p></td><td><p>5%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>D) Working-class background</p></td><td><p>Not held</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>E) Black or minority background</p></td><td><p>5%</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p><em>Date of report: 31/12/16 (run quarterly)</em></p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-03-01T12:55:25.45Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694294/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694294/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694294/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-02-24","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy: Senior Civil Servants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what proportion of senior civil servants of his Department are (a) men, (b) women, (c) disabled, (d) from working-class backgrounds and (e) from black, Asian and minority ethnic backgrounds.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","65548"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694295","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-03-03","<p>The Enterprise Capital Funds' programme is currently investing in 312 businesses. This includes 169 businesses with females in leadership positions.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-03-03T10:29:12.443Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694295/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694295/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694295/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-02-24","Enterprise Capital Funds: Females","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how many and what proportion of the recipients of the Enterprise Capital Funds' programme were companies with at least one woman in a leadership position in each fiscal year since 2009-10.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","65476"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694296","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-03-03","<p>Business Finance Partnership is facilitating over £5.2 billion of funding to almost 2,000 businesses. We do not hold data on numbers of female recipients.</p><p> </p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-03-03T10:29:30.627Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694296/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694296/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694296/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-02-24","Business: Females","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how many and what proportion of the recipients of funding from the Business Finance Partnership were companies with at least one woman in a leadership position in each fiscal year since 2009-10.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","65477"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694297","HM Treasury","false","2017-03-01","<p>The Government is determined that everyone who is entitled to the National Minimum Wage (NMW) and National Living Wage (NLW) receives it. Anyone who feels they have been underpaid NMW or NLW should contact the Acas helpline on 0300 123 1100. HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) reviews all complaints referred to the department.</p><p> </p><p>HMRC does not record statistics on complaints or the outcomes of its investigations by reference to Government regions, constituencies or counties. In 2015/16, HMRC investigated 2,667 businesses, identifying £10.3m of underpaid wages for 58,080 workers.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2017-03-01T15:29:26.003Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694297/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694297/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694297/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-02-24","Pay: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many firms were investigated for alleged (a) non-payment of and (b) other breaches of national minimum or living wage legislation in each local authority in Wales in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Stephen Doughty","Cardiff South and Penarth","Stephen Doughty","65504"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694298","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-03-06","<p>The Government has no plans to make a further assessment of the merits of a statutory workplace maximum temperature. For information on the existing law and guidance on workplace temperature, I refer the hon. Member to the answer I gave on 09 September 2016 to Question UIN <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-questions-answers/?page=1&amp;max=20&amp;questiontype=AllQuestions&amp;house=commons%2clords&amp;uin=44106" target="_blank">44106</a>.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-03-06T13:25:16.427Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694298/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694298/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694298/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-02-24","Working Conditions: Temperature","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if he will make an assessment of the potential merits of a statutory maximum workplace temperature.","false","Biography information for Sarah Olney","Richmond Park","Sarah Olney","65445"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694299","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-03-01","<p>The Angel CoFund invests, on a commercial basis, in to companies that meet its investment criteria and are approved by its Investment Committee. As at the end December 2016, the Angel CoFund had invested and committed over £32 million, alongside a further £142 million from business angels and other investors, providing support for 68 businesses. While the specific data requested is not available, information on the portfolio is available here:</p><p> </p><p><a href="http://www.angelcofund.co.uk/news/2016-03-01/angel-cofund-four-years-on" target="_blank">http://www.angelcofund.co.uk/news/2016-03-01/angel-cofund-four-years-on</a></p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-03-01T11:27:24.847Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694299/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694299/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694299/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-02-24","Business Angel Co-investment Fund: Females","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how many and what proportion of the recipients of funding from the Business Angel Co-Investment Fund were (a) female entrepreneurs or (b) syndicates which included at least one female entrepreneur in each fiscal year since the Business Angels scheme was established.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","65494"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694300","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-03-01","<p>During the current fiscal year (2016/17) to date the Business Support Helpline has gathered gender details from 28,103 customers.</p><p> </p><p>The gender breakdown is as follow:</p><p>Female 13,788 (49%)</p><p>Male 14,315 (51%)</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-03-01T15:43:10.43Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694300/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694300/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694300/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-02-24","Business: Females","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how many and what proportion of callers to the Business Support Helpline were women in the latest fiscal year for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","65473"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694301","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-03-01","<p>The table below shows how many and proportion of start up loans given to women.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Fiscal Year</p></td><td><p>Start up Loans</p></td><td><p>Percentage</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>FY 2012/13</p></td><td><p>673</p></td><td><p>37%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>FY2013/14</p></td><td><p>4684</p></td><td><p>37%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>FY2014/15</p></td><td><p>5181</p></td><td><p>38%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>FY2015/16</p></td><td><p>3724</p></td><td><p>41%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>FY2016/17(YTD 31st January 2017)</p></td><td><p>3146</p></td><td><p>40%</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-03-01T11:25:50.283Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694301/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694301/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694301/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-02-24","New Businesses: Females","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how many and what proportion of start up loans were given to women in each fiscal year since the Start Up Loans company was established.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","65496"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694302","HM Treasury","false","2017-03-01","<p>The Government does not hold this information. HM Revenue and Customs does not collect information on the number, role or gender of officers and directors of companies that apply to use the Seed Enterprise Investment Scheme.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2017-03-01T15:30:43.383Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694302/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694302/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694302/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-02-24","Seed Enterprise Investment Scheme: Females","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many and what proportion of the recipients of funding from the Seed Enterprise Investment Scheme were (a) female entrepreneurs and (b) companies with at least one woman in a leadership position in each year since that scheme was established.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","65492"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694303","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-03-01","<p>The 2016 Queen’s Awards for Enterprise saw 254 awards presented. 249 Awards were presented to companies in the categories of International Trade, Innovation and Sustainable Development. 5 Awards were presented to individuals for Enterprise Promotion, 3 of which were presented to women, equating to 60% of the 2016 Enterprise Promotion category Awards.</p><p>The Enterprise Britain Awards are open to public sector organisations rather than individuals so gender statistics are not available.</p><p> </p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-03-01T15:42:05.723Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694303/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694303/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694303/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-02-24","Business: Females","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how many and what proportion of the recipients of (a) the Queen's Award for Enterprise and (b) awards from Enterprising Britain were women in the latest year for which those respective awards were given.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","65481"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694304","Department for Education","false","2017-03-06","<p>The Inspiring the Future scheme is a programme run by the Education and Employers Taskforce and connects schools with volunteers from the world of work.</p><p> </p><p>As the Education and Employers Taskforce is an independent charity we do not hold information on the numbers and proportion of the enterprise champions recruited onto the scheme that were women, from the financial year 2012-13. Information about the scheme can be found on their website at <a href="http://www.inspiringthefuture.org" target="_blank">www.inspiringthefuture.org</a> or by contacting the company directly at enquiries@inspiringthefuture.org.</p>","Harlow","Robert Halfon",,"2017-03-06T17:27:09.933Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694304/answer","Biography information for Robert Halfon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694304/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694304/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-02-24","Business: Females","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many and what proportion of the enterprise champions recruited through the Inspiring the Future scheme were women in each fiscal year since 2012-13.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","65482"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694305","Department for Education","false","2017-03-06","<p>Young Enterprise runs programmes that link schools and employers to develop young people’s personal and business skills.</p><p> </p><p>As Young Enterprise is an independent charity we do not hold information on the numbers and proportion of women that are registered with them online. Information about the charity’s work can be found on their website at www.young-enterprise.org.uk or by contacting the company directly at info@y-e.org.uk.</p><p> </p>","Harlow","Robert Halfon",,"2017-03-06T17:29:59.333Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694305/answer","Biography information for Robert Halfon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694305/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694305/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-02-24","Young Enterprise: Females","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many and what proportion of people registered online with Young Enterprise are women.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","65483"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694306","Department for International Trade","false","2017-03-06","<p>The Prime Minister set out a clear and comprehensive plan for our future relationship with Europe including, as a priority, the pursuit of a bold and ambitious Free Trade Agreement.</p><p> </p><p>We are closely engaged with stakeholders in the automotive and other sectors to understand their interests in the UK’s future trading arrangements with the EU and to ensure the best possible outcome for UK businesses and consumers.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands","65443","2017-03-06T14:41:33.223Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694306/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694306/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694306/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-02-24","Motor Vehicles: Manufacturing Industries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what assessment he has made of the potential effect of the draft World Trade Organisation schedules on the cost-efficiency of UK exporters of component parts for the automotive sector should those schedules apply to UK trade with the EU after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Barry Gardiner","Brent North","Barry Gardiner","65444"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694307","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-03-06","<p>Once we have left the EU, maintaining the UK’s high standards of food safety will remain a priority.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-03-06T12:25:23.127Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694307/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694307/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694307/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-02-24","Genetically Modified Organisms: USA","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, whether it is her policy to maintain current food safety, sanitary and phytosanitary controls for (a) chlorinated chicken, (b) hormone enhanced beef and (c) genetically modified goods in the event of any future UK-US trade agreement.","false","Biography information for Barry Gardiner","Brent North","Barry Gardiner","65446"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694308","Department for International Trade","false","2017-03-06","<p>As my Rt hon Friend the Secretary of State for International Trade made clear in his Written Ministerial Statement on 5 December 2016, HCWS316, we will seek to replicate our commitments at the World Trade Organisation as we leave the EU.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2017-03-06T14:49:52.14Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694308/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694308/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694308/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-02-24","Agriculture: Subsidies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, whether his plans for World Trade Organisation schedule liberalisation include lower levels of subsidies for the UK's agricultural sector after 2020.","false","Biography information for Barry Gardiner","Brent North","Barry Gardiner","65441"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694309","Department for International Trade","false","2017-03-06","<p>As my Rt hon Friend the Secretary of State for International Trade made clear in his Written Ministerial Statement on 5 December 2016, HCWS316, we will seek to replicate our commitments at the World Trade Organisation as we leave the EU. This Department is working closely with the Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs and the devolved administrations to ensure that UK farmers face a smooth transition as we leave the EU.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2017-03-06T17:58:13.497Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694309/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694309/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694309/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-02-24","Agriculture","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, whether his plans for World Trade Organisation schedule liberalisation include the agriculture and food production industry; and what discussions he has had with the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs on commissioning an assessment of the effects of that liberalisation on UK farmers.","false","Biography information for Barry Gardiner","Brent North","Barry Gardiner","65442"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694310","Department for International Trade","false","2017-03-06","<p>The Prime Minister set out a clear and comprehensive plan for our future relationship with Europe including, as a priority, the pursuit of a bold and ambitious Free Trade Agreement.</p><p> </p><p>We are closely engaged with stakeholders in the automotive and other sectors to understand their interests in the UK’s future trading arrangements with the EU and to ensure the best possible outcome for UK businesses and consumers.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands","65444","2017-03-06T14:41:33.3Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694310/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694310/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694310/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-02-24","Motor Vehicles: Manufacturing Industries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what assessment he has made of the potential effect of the draft World Trade Organisation schedules on the cost-efficiency of UK automotive industry exporters should those schedules apply to UK trade with the EU after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Barry Gardiner","Brent North","Barry Gardiner","65443"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694311","Department for International Trade","false","2017-03-06","<p>UK Export Finance (UKEF) is open to applications for its support from all UK companies looking to export and is raising awareness of its offer among businesses in all sectors and in all regions of the UK. UKEF does not currently collect information on the gender of staff in leadership positions for the companies that it supports.</p><p> </p><p>Where such information is not commercially sensitive, the companies supported by UKEF since 2009-2010 are listed in its Annual Report and Accounts which are presented to Parliament.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2017-03-06T17:56:26.643Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694311/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694311/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694311/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-02-24","Business: Females","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, how many and what proportion of the recipients of support from UK Export Finance were companies with at least one woman in a leadership position in each fiscal year since 2009-10.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","65475"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694312","Department for International Trade","false","2017-03-06","<p>The proportion of senior civil servants working in the Department for International Trade and the UK Export Finance in the categories requested is shown in the table below.</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Category</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Proportion*</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Men</p></td><td><p>63.5%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Women</p></td><td><p>36.5%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Disabled</p></td><td><p>4.7%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>from Black, Asian and minority ethnic backgrounds</p></td><td><p>3.7%</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>* as at 12 January 2017</p><p> </p><p>This data is based on the self-declared information of the senior civil servants, and therefore may not be truly representative.</p><p>Data on the social background of our senior civil servants is not held centrally. To capture and analyse this would incur disproportionate costs.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2017-03-06T17:56:39.3Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694312/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694312/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694312/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-02-24","Department for International Trade: Senior Civil Servants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what proportion of senior civil servants of his Department are (a) men, (b) women, (c) disabled, (d) from working-class backgrounds and (e) from black, Asian and minority ethnic backgrounds.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","65562"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694313","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-03-06","<p>The information requested cannot be released as individuals may be identifiable. The Department for Exiting the European Union is committed to the creation of a diverse and inclusive working environment to ensure staff do not face any barriers to success, and all staff feel supported at work. As such, the Department is committed to the steps established in the 2016 Talent Action Plan to help the Civil Service become the most inclusive employer in the UK. The department is also committed to working with a diverse range of external organisations, to ensure our work reflects a broad range of opinions across the UK.</p><p> </p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2017-03-06T14:33:44.113Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694313/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694313/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694313/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-02-24","Department for Exiting the European Union: Senior Civil Servants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what proportion of senior civil servants of his Department are (a) men, (b) women, (c) disabled, (d) from working-class backgrounds and (e) from black, Asian and minority ethnic backgrounds.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","65556"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694314","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-03-02","<p>We want the UK to have the greatest possible barrier-free trade with the EU, delivered through a bold and ambitious Free Trade Agreement.</p><p><strong><br></strong>After we have left the EU, we want to ensure that we can take advantage of the opportunity to negotiate our own preferential trade agreements around the world. We will not be bound by the EU’s Common External Tariff or participate in the Common Commercial Policy. But we do want to ensure that cross-border trade with the EU is as frictionless and seamless as possible. These are our guiding objectives for the future customs arrangements with the EU.<strong><br></strong></p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2017-03-02T16:40:10.257Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694314/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694314/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694314/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-02-24","Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what estimate he has made of the cost to the public purse of leaving the Common Commercial Policy and the Common External Tariff as part of his Department's negotiations on the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Yasmin Qureshi","Bolton South East","Yasmin Qureshi","65518"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694315","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-03-06","<p>The safety of the British public is the top priority for the Government. It is in all our interests that we continue our deep cooperation with the EU and its Member States to tackle crime and terrorism.<br><br>As the recent White Paper made clear, the Government will look to negotiate the best deal we can with the EU to cooperate in the fight against crime and terrorism. We will seek a strong and close future relationship with the EU, with a focus on operational and practical cross-border cooperation.<strong><br></strong></p>","Clwyd West","Mr David Jones",,"2017-03-06T14:27:09.693Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694315/answer","Biography information for Mr David Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694315/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694315/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-02-24","European Arrest Warrants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what assessment he has made of the potential effect of leaving the European Arrest Warrant system on the effectiveness of the criminal justice system as part of his Department's negotiations for leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Yasmin Qureshi","Bolton South East","Yasmin Qureshi","65515"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694316","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-03-02","<p>We want the UK to have the greatest possible barrier-free trade with the EU, delivered through a bold and ambitious Free Trade Agreement.</p><p><br>The Prime Minister has set out our intention to negotiate a new customs arrangement with the EU. We have an open mind about the form of that arrangement, but it is in both the UK and EU's interest that cross-border trade be as frictionless as possible. We will be aiming to minimise the impact of any additional customs procedures on goods trade between the UK and EU.<br><br><br><br></p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2017-03-02T12:45:40.117Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694316/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694316/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694316/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-02-24","Exports: Origin Marking","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what assessment he has made of the potential costs to British manufacturers of being subject to non-preferential rules of origin on exports to the EU after the UK has left the EU.","false","Biography information for Yasmin Qureshi","Bolton South East","Yasmin Qureshi","65537"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694317","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-03-06","<p>The Department works closely with the marine engineering and manufacturing sector, which includes the yacht building industry. The Ministerial Working Group for Maritime Growth continues to engage with the industry on the issues and opportunities for the maritime sector resulting from the UK leaving the EU.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2017-03-06T14:34:40.157Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694317/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694317/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694317/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-02-24","Shipbuilding","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what assessment his Department has made of the effect on the luxury yacht building industry in the UK since the EU referendum.","false","Biography information for Oliver Colvile","Plymouth, Sutton and Devonport","Oliver Colvile","65448"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694325","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-03-10","<p>The Government has not yet taken a decision as to the timing of any review of the waste water National Policy Statement.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2017-03-10T14:22:26.547Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694325/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694325/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694325/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-02-24","Sewage: Water Treatment","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government when they plan to review the National Policy Statement (NPS) for Waste Water, published on 9 February 2012, in the light of the statement in that NPS that it was expected that the Secretary of State would review the NPS approximately every five years.","false","Biography information for Lord Berkeley",,"Lord Berkeley","HL5599"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694326","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-03-06","<p>The Prime Minister has set out clearly that she is committed to building a country that works for everyone – not just the privileged few.</p><p> </p><p>Tackling child poverty and disadvantage is a priority for this government. To do this, we need to focus on the root causes of poverty and disadvantage. This is why we have introduced two statutory measures of parental worklessness and children’s educational attainment – to drive action on the two areas that can make the biggest difference to children’s outcomes. <br></p><p>As part of our approach, we fully recognise the importance of the right intervention, at the right time. This is why, for example, we are developing a new approach to parental conflict. It is based on the latest evidence from the Early Intervention Foundation that children exposed to frequent, intense and poorly resolved conflict between their parents are at risk of poorer long term outcomes.</p>",,"Lord Henley",,"2017-03-06T15:57:33.587Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694326/answer","Biography information for Lord Henley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694326/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694326/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-02-24","Disadvantaged: Children","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what steps they are taking to prioritise preventative policy-making in their poverty and early intervention programmes.","false","Biography information for Lord Bird",,"Lord Bird","HL5600"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694327","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-03-09","<p>Many dog rehoming centres are members of the Association for Dogs &amp; Cats Homes (ADCH) which has minimum standards in regard to the responsible re-homing of dogs and cats. The Government has no proposals to introduce additional obligatory regulatory standards. I would encourage anyone thinking of acquiring a dog from a re-homing centre to approach a member of the ADCH first.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble","HL5602","2017-03-09T16:20:36.327Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694327/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694327/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694327/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-02-24","Dangerous Dogs","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they are planning to make provision for the introduction of national or local standards to regulate the re-homing of dogs which could pose a risk to their new owners.","false","Biography information for Lord Redesdale",,"Lord Redesdale","HL5601"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694328","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-03-09","<p>Many dog rehoming centres are members of the Association for Dogs &amp; Cats Homes (ADCH) which has minimum standards in regard to the responsible re-homing of dogs and cats. The Government has no proposals to introduce additional obligatory regulatory standards. I would encourage anyone thinking of acquiring a dog from a re-homing centre to approach a member of the ADCH first.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble","HL5601","2017-03-09T16:20:36.387Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694328/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694328/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694328/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-02-24","Dangerous Dogs","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they are planning to make provision for the introduction of national or local standards to oblige dog re-homing centres to make owners aware of any previous history of attacks on humans or other dogs by any dog being considered for re-homing.","false","Biography information for Lord Redesdale",,"Lord Redesdale","HL5602"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694329","Department for International Development","false","2017-03-06","<p>DFID is providing £4.7 million to the United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees to deliver the 2017 Regional Refugee and Migrant Response Plan for Europe. This includes protection from sexual and gender based violence and supports access to sexual and reproductive health services in Greece but is not earmarked to a specific agency.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2017-03-06T17:38:13.193Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694329/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694329/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694329/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-02-24","Greece: Refugees","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what action they will take to ensure that the UN Population Fund’s requirement for $2.996 million to provide sexual and reproductive health and gender-based violence services in Greece, as set out on page 66 of the UNHCR <i>Regional Refugee and Migration Response Plan for Europe January to December 2017</i>, is met; and how much they will contribute towards meeting this requirement.","false","Biography information for Baroness Tonge",,"Baroness Tonge","HL5603"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694330","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-03-08","<p>Data published by my department on the impact of employment on reduced re-offending relies on data drawn together from across the Criminal Justice System, supplemented by data on the employment and benefit status of offenders from a data sharing agreement between MoJ, DWP and HMRC.</p><p> </p><p>That data does not enable any comparative assessment of reoffending rates for ex-prisoners who have or have not undertaken enterprise courses.</p>",,"Lord Keen of Elie",,"2017-03-08T15:11:47.94Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694330/answer","Biography information for Lord Keen of Elie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694330/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694330/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-02-24","Reoffenders","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment has been made of reoffending rates for (1) ex-prisoners who have undertaken enterprise courses, and (2) those who have not.","false","Biography information for Lord Watts",,"Lord Watts","HL5604"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694331","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-03-09","<p>Charities and social enterprises play an important role in the government’s mission of building an economy that works for everyone. The government is building on its role as a world leader in soc`ial enterprise by championing procurement for social value, supporting social enterprise awareness campaigns, building the social investment market, using social enterprises to address issues at scale and expanding the social investment tax relief.</p>",,"Baroness Buscombe",,"2017-03-09T16:00:56.167Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694331/answer","Biography information for Baroness Buscombe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694331/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694331/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-02-24","Social Enterprises: Offenders","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the answer by Lord Ashton of Hyde on 10 January (HL Deb, col 1856), what steps they are taking to enable more private, local authority and charity investment in social enterprises which support or employ ex-prisoners.","false","Biography information for Lord Watts",,"Lord Watts","HL5605"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694332","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-03-09","<p>A full report on the Diffuse Mesothelioma Payment Scheme (DMPS), including details on how the levy is estimated can be found in the Annual Review</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/diffuse-mesothelioma-payment-scheme-annual-review-2015-to-2016" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/diffuse-mesothelioma-payment-scheme-annual-review-2015-to-2016</a></p><p> </p><p>1) The amount of the levy raised through the provision of Mesothelioma Act 2014 in respect of the DMPS is:</p><ul><li>2014/15 = £32m</li><li>2015/16 = £23.2m</li><li>2016/17 = £40.4m (Eligible insurers notified January 2017)</li></ul><p> </p><p>2) In 2014/15 a total of 24.2m was paid to successful applicants. In 2015/16 a total of £29.7m was paid to successful applicants. 2016/17 is not yet calculated.</p><p> </p><p>3) The difference between the sum raised through the levy and the amount paid out to applicants in compensation is used in one of the following ways:</p><ul><li>To repay as compensation recoveries (the amount is determined by the Department’s Compensation Recovery Unit);</li><li>To pay a scheme administrator;</li><li>Any balance is accounted for as either an under or over levy for successive year’s estimated levy amount.</li></ul>",,"Lord Henley",,"2017-03-09T15:15:19.71Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694332/answer","Biography information for Lord Henley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694332/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694332/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-02-24","Mesothelioma: Compensation","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government for each year since the passing of the Mesothelioma Act 2014 (1) how much was raised through the provision in the Act to impose a levy on employers' insurers to provide compensation to sufferers from mesothelioma, (2) how much of that sum was paid out in compensation to sufferers from mesothelioma, and (3) what happened to any difference between the sum raised through the levy and the amount paid out in compensation.","false","Biography information for Lord Wills",,"Lord Wills","HL5606"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694333","HM Treasury","false","2017-03-09","<p>Tackling money laundering is a UK-wide issue and receives a cross-Government response. HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) supervises specific sectors, and investigates high risk activity, in close collaboration with other supervisors and law enforcement agencies.</p><p> </p><p>Effectiveness is best assessed in the round. The latest UK national risk assessment of money laundering and terrorist financing is published on gov.uk<sup><sup>[1]</sup></sup>. The assessment factors in information about the impact of anti-money laundering activities, including contributions from across HMRC and other organisations.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>[1] <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/468210/UK_NRA_October_2015_final_web.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/468210/UK_NRA_October_2015_final_web.pdf</a></p><p> </p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2017-03-09T14:06:08.903Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694333/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694333/answer","UK_NRA_October_2015_final_web.pdf","UK_NRA_October_2015_final_web.pdf","The latest UK national risk assessment of money la","The latest UK national risk assessment of money la","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694333/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-02-24","Money Laundering","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Baroness Neville-Rolfe on 20 February (HL5284), what assessment they have made of the impact of HM Revenue and Customs enforcement actions in relation to money laundering.","false","Biography information for Lord Wills",,"Lord Wills","HL5607"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694334","Department for International Development","false","2017-03-06","<p>The International Organization for Migration already has a substantial presence in Tripoli and other parts of Libya, and so has the United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees. Both organisations receive substantial funding from the UK for their humanitarian activities, including assistance and advice to vulnerable migrants and refugees, as well as support to return home for those wishing to do so. Their capacity to expand operations is a matter for the organisations themselves.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2017-03-06T17:39:34.897Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694334/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694334/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694334/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-02-24","Libya: International Organization for Migration","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of whether a new International Organisation for Migration dedicated centre, in or near Tripoli, Libya, would help to identify genuine refugees and encourage other migrants to return home.","false","Biography information for Lord Hylton",,"Lord Hylton","HL5608"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694335","Department for International Development","false","2017-03-08","<p>DFID has allocated £5 million to the International Organization for Migration to provide life-saving assistance to migrants and refugees in Libya, Sudan and the Balkans. This includes support for them to return home if they wish to do so and improvements to conditions in Libyan detention centres. The United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees has been assigned £9.8 million for their work in Greece, the Balkans and North Africa, to improve refugee status determination processes, and support local integration and assisted voluntary returns. The remainder has been allocated to trusted partners to meet the needs of vulnerable women and girls, enable rapid responses to new crises, such as freezing winter conditions in the Balkans, and improve the evidence base to enable the humanitarian system to respond more effectively.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2017-03-08T16:43:49.35Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694335/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694335/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694335/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-02-24","Mediterranean Region: Immigrants","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how the £30 million of aid for refugees and migrants in the Mediterranean region, announced by the Prime Minister on 3 February, will be divided between the International Organization for Migration, the UNHCR, and other groups.","false","Biography information for Lord Hylton",,"Lord Hylton","HL5609"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694336","Home Office","false","2017-03-10","<p>In November 2010, the Government secured a mediated without prejudice settlement of the civil damages claims brought by detainees held at Guantanamo Bay (<em>Official Report </em>col. 752).</p><p>The details of that settlement were made subject to a legally binding confidentiality agreement. We are therefore unable to confirm the terms of that settlement agreement, including the number of individuals involved, their nationalities, or the level of payments made.</p><p> </p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2017-03-10T11:09:08.043Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694336/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694336/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694336/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-02-24","Guantanamo Bay: Detainees","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many British citizens have received compensation following a period of detention at Guantanamo Bay; and how much has been paid out in total.","false","Biography information for Lord Laird",,"Lord Laird","HL5610"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694337","HM Treasury","false","2017-03-06","<p>The Public Works Loan Board (PWLB) is a statutory body that issues loans to local authorities in England, Scotland and Wales from the National Loans Fund. The PWLB is not required to collect information on the specific reasons that local authorities borrow from it, and so it does not hold information about the amount of lending that has been used for acquisition of commercial real estate.</p><p>Before it can advance a loan to a local authority, the PWLB requires formal assurance from the authority that the loan is within their borrowing powers and the relevant legislation. Local authorities are required to have regard to the Prudential Code when they borrow from the PWLB or from any other lender. The main objective of the Prudential Code is to ensure, within a clear framework, that the capital investment plans of local authorities are affordable, prudent and sustainable. Responsibility for local authority spending and borrowing decisions lies with locally-elected council Members, who are democratically accountable to their electorates.</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2017-03-06T16:11:04.573Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694337/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694337/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694337/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-02-24","Public Works Loan Board","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how much has been lent by the Public Works Loan Board (PWLB) to local authorities for the acquisition of commercial real estate for investment purposes, from 2011 to 2016 inclusive; and how the PWLB is monitoring the risk from such investments.","false","Biography information for Lord Myners",,"Lord Myners","HL5611"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694338","The Senior Deputy Speaker","false","2017-03-07","<p>Access to the Religion of Peace website has been blocked on the Parliamentary Estate because it has been classified as a religion-based hate website by the Parliamentary Digital Service’s industry standard categorising service. As a result there are no plans for the website to be unblocked.</p>",,"Lord McFall of Alcluith",,"2017-03-07T15:14:36.683Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694338/answer","Biography information for Lord McFall of Alcluith","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694338/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694338/answer",,,,,"204",,"Senior Deputy Speaker (HoL)","2017-02-24","Parliament: Internet","2","House of Lords","To ask the Senior Deputy Speaker, further to his Written Answer on 1 February (HL 4961), whether he will give an instruction for the unblocking of the Religion of Peace website on the Parliamentary Estate; and if not, why not.","false","Biography information for Lord Pearson of Rannoch",,"Lord Pearson of Rannoch","HL5612"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694339","The Senior Deputy Speaker","false","2017-03-07","<p>For the 2015-16 financial year the cost of the House of Lords excluding Estates and Works expenditure and non-cash costs (e.g. depreciation) was £67,932,000. As at 31 March 2016 there were 814 members, making the average cost of a member on this basis £83,000.</p>",,"Lord McFall of Alcluith",,"2017-03-07T15:14:02.597Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694339/answer","Biography information for Lord McFall of Alcluith","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694339/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694339/answer",,,,,"204",,"Senior Deputy Speaker (HoL)","2017-02-24","Peers: Per Capita Costs","2","House of Lords","To ask the Senior Deputy Speaker what is the average cost to the British taxpayer, including salary and expenses but excluding building maintenance costs, of a member of the House of Lords.","false","Biography information for Lord Pearson of Rannoch",,"Lord Pearson of Rannoch","HL5613"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694340","HM Treasury","false","2017-03-09","<p>The terms and conditions of MEPs are set out in the Statute for Members of the European Parliament. As of July 2016 the gross monthly salary of an MEP is €8,484.05. MEPs are also entitled to a monthly €4,342 general expenditure allowance covering staff and office costs, and allowances for travel and subsistence.</p><p> </p><p>As the government contributes to the EU budget as a whole and not to individual programmes or institutions, it is not possible to say how much this costs the British taxpayer.</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2017-03-09T13:52:02.18Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694340/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694340/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694340/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-02-24","European Parliament Members: Per Capita Costs","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what is the average cost to the British taxpayer, including salary and expenses but excluding building maintenance costs, of a UK Member of the European Parliament.","false","Biography information for Lord Pearson of Rannoch",,"Lord Pearson of Rannoch","HL5614"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694341","Department of Health","false","2017-03-07","<p>The Department has commissioned independent research to investigate consumer understanding, product appeal, selection and consumption in relation to the labelling of low/reduced alcohol products. This research team is due to report back in the spring of 2017. A decision will be taken on possible future consultation and regulations once the outputs of the research have been received and reviewed.</p>",,"Lord O'Shaughnessy","HL5616 ; HL5617","2017-03-07T12:23:06.987Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694341/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Shaughnessy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694341/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694341/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-02-24","Drinks: Labelling","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what plans they have for public consultation on the labelling of low alcohol, alcohol-free, non-alcoholic and de-alcoholised drinks as part of the Food Information Regulations 2014.","false","Biography information for Lord Rennard",,"Lord Rennard","HL5615"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694342","Department of Health","false","2017-03-07","<p>The Department has commissioned independent research to investigate consumer understanding, product appeal, selection and consumption in relation to the labelling of low/reduced alcohol products. This research team is due to report back in the spring of 2017. A decision will be taken on possible future consultation and regulations once the outputs of the research have been received and reviewed.</p>",,"Lord O'Shaughnessy","HL5615 ; HL5617","2017-03-07T12:23:07.047Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694342/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Shaughnessy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694342/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694342/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-02-24","Food: Labelling","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they will ensure that the new guidelines to update the Food Information Regulations 2014 are reflective of modern manufacturing processes, provide consumers with the information they need to make informed decisions, and eliminate confusion for retailers.","false","Biography information for Lord Rennard",,"Lord Rennard","HL5616"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694343","Department of Health","false","2017-03-07","<p>The Department has commissioned independent research to investigate consumer understanding, product appeal, selection and consumption in relation to the labelling of low/reduced alcohol products. This research team is due to report back in the spring of 2017. A decision will be taken on possible future consultation and regulations once the outputs of the research have been received and reviewed.</p>",,"Lord O'Shaughnessy","HL5615 ; HL5616","2017-03-07T12:23:07.11Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694343/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Shaughnessy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694343/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694343/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-02-24","Drinks: Labelling","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they will consider simplifying the Food Information Regulations 2014 to allow UK producers to label their 0.5 per cent alcohol by volume or lower products alcohol-free in line with other countries.","false","Biography information for Lord Rennard",,"Lord Rennard","HL5617"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694344","Department of Health","false","2017-03-08","<p>The 2016 United Kingdom Chief Medical Officers’ low risk drinking guidelines provide the public with the most up-to-date scientific information to help people make informed choices about their own drinking. The Government is committed to working with industry to address concerns over any irresponsible promotions, advertising and marketing of alcohol.</p>",,"Lord O'Shaughnessy",,"2017-03-08T15:15:50.187Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694344/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Shaughnessy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694344/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694344/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-02-24","Licensed Premises","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what steps they are taking to encourage the sale of more low-alcohol or non-alcoholic drinks in licensed venues; and what assessment they have made of the potential health benefits of such a policy.","false","Biography information for Lord Rennard",,"Lord Rennard","HL5618"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694345","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-03-10","<p>Local authorities have powers under the Animal Welfare Act 2006 to enforce animal welfare and, at a district level, local authorities regulate certain licensed activities involving animals. At a county level, local authorities also carry out various functions in relation to on-farm animal welfare. The Government does not hold records as to what degree individual local authorities enforce animal welfare laws. It is up to each local authority to decide what level of enforcement they will provide in relation to animal welfare based upon local priorities.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2017-03-10T12:01:02.037Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694345/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694345/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694345/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-02-24","Animal Welfare","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the answer by Lord Gardiner of Kimble on 16 January (HL Deb, col 7), how many local authorities have enforced animal welfare legislation in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Baroness Smith of Basildon",,"Baroness Smith of Basildon","HL5619"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694346","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-03-10","<p>The number of defendants proceeded against at Magistrates Courts for offences under Section 4 of the Animal Welfare Act 2006, in England and Wales, from 2010 to 2015, can be viewed in the table. Data for 2016 is planned for publication in May 2017.</p><p><strong>Defendants proceeded against at Magistrates Courts for offences under S4 Animal Welfare Act 2006, England and Wales, 2010 to 2015 (1)(2)</strong></p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>2010</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2011</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2012</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2013</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2014</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2015</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>1,077</p></td><td><p>1,277</p></td><td><p>1,385</p></td><td><p>1,266</p></td><td><p>1,016</p></td><td><p>755</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>(1) The statistics relate to persons for whom these offences were the principal offences for which they were dealt with. When a defendant has been found guilty of two or more offences the principal offence is the offence for which the heaviest penalty is imposed. Where the same disposal is imposed for two or more offences, the offence selected is the offence for which the statutory maximum penalty is the most severe.</p><p> </p><p>(2) Every effort is made to ensure that the figures presented are accurate and complete. However, it is important to note that these data have been extracted from large administrative data systems generated by the courts and police forces. As a consequence, care should be taken to ensure data collection processes and their inevitable limitations are taken into account when those data are used.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Source: Justice Statistics Analytical Services - Ministry of Justice.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2017-03-10T13:37:59.433Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694346/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694346/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694346/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-02-24","Animal Welfare: Prosecutions","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many prosecutions for animal cruelty there have been in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Baroness Smith of Basildon",,"Baroness Smith of Basildon","HL5620"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694347","Cabinet Office","false","2017-03-09","<p>The Government does not hold this data. Responsibility for such partnerships rests with local Electoral Registration Officer’s.</p>",,"Lord Young of Cookham",,"2017-03-09T17:08:27.577Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694347/answer","Biography information for Lord Young of Cookham","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694347/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694347/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-02-24","Schools: Electoral Register","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government (1) how many, and (2) what proportion of, schools in the UK work in partnership with electoral registration offices.","false","Biography information for Baroness Smith of Basildon",,"Baroness Smith of Basildon","HL5621"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694348","Department of Health","false","2017-03-06","<p>This information is not held centrally.</p>",,"Lord O'Shaughnessy",,"2017-03-06T14:40:04.457Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694348/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Shaughnessy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694348/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694348/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-02-24","Patients: Transport","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how much has been spent on transporting patients between medical facilities in England in order to receive care, for each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Baroness Smith of Basildon",,"Baroness Smith of Basildon","HL5622"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694349","Department for Education","false","2017-03-13","<p>The Department does not collect data on children who are not registered pupils at a school and do not complete their education.</p>",,"Lord Nash",,"2017-03-13T14:31:33.09Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694349/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694349/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/694349/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-02-24","Children: Poverty","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many children who were living below the poverty line during their school age years did not complete their education in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Baroness Smith of Basildon",,"Baroness Smith of Basildon","HL5623"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693639","Cabinet Office","false","2017-03-02","<p>The blog post in question was published in November 2016 and contains the personal reflections of Ms Kempster, who contracted with the Government Digital Service during 2015.</p><p>I believe that the ambitious approach set out in the Government Transformation Strategy, which was published last month, is absolutely the correct one. The Strategy sets out our priorities for the remainder of this Parliament and explains the critical role that the Government Digital Service will play. This includes equipping civil servants with the digital tools, techniques and skills which are so vital in ensuring public services work better for citizens.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2017-03-02T13:08:24.523Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693639/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693639/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693639/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-02-23","Government Digital Service","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, if he will make an assessment of the implications for his policies on the Government Digital Service of the findings of the blog post by Ann Kempster entitled So long and thanks for all the cheese.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","65298"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693640","Cabinet Office","false","2017-03-01","<p>Our policy on how we approach polling or any other research remains unchanged since June 2016. Where research is deemed necessary, we will select the most appropriate methodology and commission research in line with industry standard guidelines (as set out in the Market Research Society (MRS) Code of Conduct). All agencies on our research frameworks operate to standards set out in this Code.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2017-03-01T11:54:30.907Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693640/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693640/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693640/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-02-23","Opinion Polls","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what research his Department has conducted into the methodology used for polls conducted by his Department since 24 June 2016.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","65329"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693641","Cabinet Office","false","2017-03-02","<p>The list of Government owned freeholds in the Central Glasgow constituency drawn from the central database of Government properties and land across the UK, ePIMS™ available at <a href="http://dat.gov.uk/" target="_blank">dat.gov.uk</a>. A number of these are land holdings owned by the Department of Transport and as such there are no addresses held for these records.</p><p>Information on the Government Estate including a mapping service is published online at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/find-government-property." target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/find-government-property.</a></p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2017-03-02T13:10:49.93Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693641/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693641/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693641/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-02-23","Government: Assets","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, pursuant to the Answer of 22 February 2017 to Question 63839, on Government: Assets, what the addresses or locations are of the 68 freehold land holdings in Glasgow Central constituency.","false","Biography information for Alison Thewliss","Glasgow Central","Alison Thewliss","65416"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693642","HM Treasury","false","2017-03-03","<p>I am pleased to confirm the government will soon be launching Tax-Free Childcare which will allow working families to receive up to £2,000 childcare support per child, per year. The new scheme will roll out gradually following the completion of the current Trial.</p><p>Tax-Free Childcare will be rolled out to all eligible families before the end of 2017 in a safe and managed way to ensure that the system runs smoothly for parents.</p><p> </p><p>The average benefit accruing to families from the proposed Tax-Free Childcare scheme is estimated to be around £800 per year.</p><p> </p><p>The estimated cost of Tax-Free Childcare in each year of this parliament is shown in the table below.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>2016-17</p></td><td><p>2017-18</p></td><td><p>2018-19</p></td><td><p>2019-20</p></td><td><p>2020-21</p></td><td><p>2021-22</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Cost (£bn)</p></td><td><p>0.0</p></td><td><p>0.6</p></td><td><p>0.8</p></td><td><p>0.9</p></td><td><p>0.9</p></td><td><p>1.0</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>These estimates are published in the Office for Budget Responsibility’s Economic and Fiscal Outlook - November 2016.</p><p><a href="http://www.budgetresponsibility.org.uk/efo/economic-and-fiscal-outlook-november-2016/" target="_blank">www.budgetresponsibility.org.uk/efo/economic-and-fiscal-outlook-november-2016/</a></p><p> </p><p>As set out at Autumn Statement 2016, once the scheme is fully rolled out, the government will review its operation to ensure it is delivering as intended and to assess the benefit it is delivering for working parents. We will also publish details about the numbers of families taking-up the scheme.</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","65390 ; 65396 ; 65397 ; 65398","2017-03-03T10:23:48.9Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693642/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693642/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693642/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-02-23","Children: Day Care","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate he has made of the average benefit that will accrue to families from the proposed tax-free childcare scheme.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","65391"
