"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693711","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-03-03","<p>The Department does not hold information on the number of commercial companies that retain individuals' personal data. The Data Protection Act 1998 (DPA) requires every data controller who is processing personal data to register with the Information Commissioner's Office (ICO) unless they are exempt. Failure to do so is a criminal offence. Information on registration can be found on the ICO's website at: www.ico.org.uk</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-03-03T14:03:07.237Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693711/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693711/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693711/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-02-23","Business: Data Protection","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what information her Department holds on the number of commercial companies that retain individuals' personal data.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","65357"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693712","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-02-28","<p>Sutton United‘s and Lincoln City’s successful cup runs this season, showed that the FA cup is hugely significant for lower league &amp; non-league clubs in terms of prestige and the revenue it brings, including through TV coverage. The clubs are best placed to make representations within the FA about how the competition might offer even more value to supporters and clubs.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2017-02-28T17:07:32.707Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693712/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693712/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693712/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-02-23","Football","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, if she will hold discussions with the Football Association on how the FA Cup can best assist non-league football clubs financially.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","65330"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693713","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-03-03","<p>My Rt Hon friend the Chancellor of the Exchequer is working with the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government to provide additional support for those businesses hardest hit following the business rates revaluation.</p><p> </p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2017-03-03T10:54:09.11Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693713/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693713/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693713/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-02-23","Non-domestic Rates: Sports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what recent discussions she has had with the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government on the financial effect of business rate changes on community and amateur sports clubs.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","65295"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693714","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-03-01","<p>Industry estimates by Newzoo suggest that the global eSports market were projected to have reached $463 million in 2016. We are keen to grow eSports in the UK and are working with industry to identify opportunities in this sector.</p>","Greenwich and Woolwich","Matthew Pennycook",,"2017-03-01T10:16:00.463Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693714/answer","Biography information for Matthew Pennycook","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693714/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693714/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-02-23","Video Games","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what recent assessment her Department has made of the economic benefits of e-sports.","false","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","65241"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693715","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-03-08","<p>The majority of the Government Art Collection is displayed in Government buildings around the world, or placed on public view.</p><p>The GAC welcomes requests for loans to public exhibitions and responds positively whenever possible. Displays on the GAC premises are accessible to the public on tours of the Collection and special events such as London Open House. In addition to themed displays, visitors to the Collection are also able to see a range of other work that may be on the premises at the time of their visit.</p><p> </p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-03-08T08:58:55.593Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693715/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693715/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693715/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-02-23","Government Art Collection","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what proportion of the total Government Art Collection was loaned out or placed on public view in the last year.","false","Biography information for Tom Watson","West Bromwich East","Tom Watson","65262"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693716","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-02-28","<p>Since the implementation of a new purchase to pay system in December 2016 the Ministry of Defence has paid around half a million invoices worth nearly £7 billion to suppliers - equating to 98% of invoices. Just under 10,000 of these - or two per cent of the stated number - with a value of some £374 million, were not satisfied within 30 days.</p><p>The MOD is committed to paying all of its suppliers as promptly as possible. We recognise the impact that late payments have on suppliers and we are taking a number of actions to ensure that performance returns to, and then surpasses, usual levels.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","65266","2017-02-28T16:09:04.42Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693716/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693716/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693716/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-02-23","Defence Equipment and Support: Billing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many invoices received from suppliers to Defence Equipment and Support have not been paid in full within 30 days of their receipt since November 2016.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","65268"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693717","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-03-01","<p>When under the operational command of the Director of Special Forces, units of the Armed Forces attached to the Special Forces Support Group are subject to the same disclosure policy as other elements of the Special Forces.</p>","Sevenoaks","Sir Michael Fallon",,"2017-03-01T16:01:52.99Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693717/answer","Biography information for Sir Michael Fallon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693717/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693717/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-02-23","Armed Forces","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, whether regular units from the Army and Royal Marines are subject to parliamentary scrutiny and the War Powers Convention when those units are attached to the Special Forces Support Group.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","65279"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693718","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-02-28","<p>Ministry of Defence (MOD) policy is to pay valid and undisputed invoices within 30 calendar days, reflecting our legal obligations. Within the MOD, including Defence Equipment and Support, payment can only be made on presentation of a valid invoice.</p><p>However, as a signatory to the Prompt Payment Code, we are fully committed to paying all suppliers as quickly as possible and we aim to pay 80% of invoices within five working days. Information about MOD payment policy and our performance is published on gov.uk at the following link:</p><p>https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/ministry-of-defence-supplier-invoicing-and-payment-information.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","65267","2017-02-28T16:04:12.853Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693718/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693718/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693718/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-02-23","Ministry of Defence: Billing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what his Department's policy is on the length of time taken to pay invoices from suppliers to his Department.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","65269"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693719","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-02-28","<p>Since the implementation of a new purchase to pay system in December 2016 the Ministry of Defence has paid around half a million invoices worth nearly £7 billion to suppliers - equating to 98% of invoices. Just under 10,000 of these - or two per cent of the stated number - with a value of some £374 million, were not satisfied within 30 days.</p><p>The MOD is committed to paying all of its suppliers as promptly as possible. We recognise the impact that late payments have on suppliers and we are taking a number of actions to ensure that performance returns to, and then surpasses, usual levels.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","65268","2017-02-28T16:09:04.467Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693719/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693719/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693719/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-02-23","Defence Equipment and Support: Billing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what the total value of invoices received from suppliers to Defence Equipment and Support and unpaid within 30 days has been since November 2016.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","65266"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693720","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-02-28","<p>Ministry of Defence (MOD) policy is to pay valid and undisputed invoices within 30 calendar days, reflecting our legal obligations. Within the MOD, including Defence Equipment and Support, payment can only be made on presentation of a valid invoice.</p><p>However, as a signatory to the Prompt Payment Code, we are fully committed to paying all suppliers as quickly as possible and we aim to pay 80% of invoices within five working days. Information about MOD payment policy and our performance is published on gov.uk at the following link:</p><p>https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/ministry-of-defence-supplier-invoicing-and-payment-information.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","65269","2017-02-28T16:04:12.79Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693720/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693720/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693720/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-02-23","Defence Equipment and Support: Billing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, whether it is the policy of Defence Equipment and Support to pay suppliers for services received only upon receipt of an invoice for those services.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","65267"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693721","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-02-28","<p>Ministers were advised in October 2016 that the contract with SuperLetter.com would be terminated as the service no longer provided value for money now that usage has declined by some 98% in recent years.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2017-02-28T16:04:55.437Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693721/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693721/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693721/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-02-23","Armed Forces: Correspondence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, when he was made aware that the British Forces Post Office had cancelled its contact with SuperLetter.com to supply e-bluey.com.","false","Biography information for Anne-Marie Trevelyan","Berwick-upon-Tweed","Mrs Anne-Marie Trevelyan","65338"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693722","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-02-28","<p>In my written statement of 17 December 2015 (HCWS431) on UK embedded forces, I committed to release information on Service personnel embedded in other nations' armed forces on an annual basis, through the Ministry of Defence's Annual Report and Accounts.</p><p>An update to the table in my statement is available on page 28 of the linked report: https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/ministry-of-defence-annual-report-and-accounts-2015-to-2016. The 2016/17 Annual Report, which will include further updates, will be published later this year.</p>","Sevenoaks","Sir Michael Fallon",,"2017-02-28T16:06:38.467Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693722/answer","Biography information for Sir Michael Fallon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693722/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693722/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-02-23","Armed Forces","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, with reference to written statement HCWS431, of 17 December 2015, on UK embedded forces, when he plans to publish details of UK service personnel embedded on the armed forces of other nations.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","65361"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693723","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-02-28","<p>In support of the Coalition campaign in Iraq and Syria, British airstrikes target Daesh fighters irrespective of nationality and it is not possible to identify how many of these might have been UK Citizens. On 7 September 2015 the then Prime Minister announced that two Daesh fighters, Ruhul Amin and Reyaad Khan, who were of British nationality, had been killed in British airstrikes because they had posed a direct threat to the UK.</p>","Sevenoaks","Sir Michael Fallon",,"2017-02-28T16:05:48.653Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693723/answer","Biography information for Sir Michael Fallon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693723/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693723/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-02-23","Middle East: Military Intervention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many UK citizens have been identified by his Department as having been killed in British airstrikes on Syria and Iraq.","false","Biography information for Tim Farron","Westmorland and Lonsdale","Tim Farron","65340"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693724","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-02-28","<p>The number of e-blueys sent in each of the last 10 years is set out below.</p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Calendar Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Number of e-blueys </strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2007</p></td><td><p>1,227,452</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2008</p></td><td><p>986,473</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2009</p></td><td><p>978,890</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010</p></td><td><p>971,285</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011</p></td><td><p>952,696</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>832,035</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>643,959</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>173,622</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p>42,329</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016</p></td><td><p>36,279</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Because we are working on a number of possible options to improve welfare connectivity on deployed operations, the cost of the current contract with SuperLetter.com is commercially sensitive.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2017-02-28T16:07:48.06Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693724/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693724/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693724/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-02-23","Armed Forces: Correspondence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what the cost was to his Department of its e-bluey contract in each of the last 10 years; and how many e-blueys were sent in each of those years.","false","Biography information for Anne-Marie Trevelyan","Berwick-upon-Tweed","Mrs Anne-Marie Trevelyan","65337"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693725","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-03-02","<p>The Coalition are providing air support to Syrian Democratic Forces who began operations to isolate Daesh's stronghold in Raqqah on 5 November 2016. Since then, Syrian Democratic Forces have made considerable progress and are now less than ten kilometres from the outskirts of the city, increasingly constraining Daesh's freedom of manoeuvre. It will continue to be a long and difficult fight but Daesh have already lost some 30% of the territory they once controlled in Syria and our strategy to take the fight to Daesh in both Syria and Iraq is working.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2017-03-02T16:07:12.903Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693725/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693725/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693725/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-02-23","Syria: Military Intervention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what progress Coalition forces have made on recapturing Raqqa.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","65420"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693726","Department for Education","false","2017-02-28","<p>Statistics on truancy are published by the Ministry of Justice in the “Criminal justice statistics outcomes by offence data tool”, available at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/criminal-justice-system-statistics-quarterly-december-2015" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/criminal-justice-system-statistics-quarterly-december-2015</a>.</p><p> </p><p>The number of defendants proceeded at court for the offences of truancy (parent failure to secure attendance of child) was 20,808 in England and Wales in 2015. The number of offenders found guilty was 15,649. Similarly, the number of offenders sentenced was 15,649; out of these, 12,095 offenders were sentenced to a court fine, and 8 offenders were given an immediate custody sentence.</p><p> </p><p>The average level of fine for truancy was £184 in 2015. The lowest fine was up to £25, and the highest fine was over £750 and up to £1,000.</p><p> </p><p>The average custodial sentence length for truancy was 1.3 months in 2015, and all custodial sentences given were for 3 months or less.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson",,"2017-02-28T17:46:14.453Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693726/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693726/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693726/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-02-23","Truancy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, (a) how many parents were prosecuted for truancy, (b) how many of those people were found guilty, (c) how many of those convicted were (i) fined and (ii) imprisoned, (d) what the (iii) highest, (iv) lowest and (v) average level of fine imposed was for those who received fines and (e) what the (vi) longest, (vii) shortest and (viii) average length of custodial sentence was for those people who received one.","false","Biography information for John Pugh","Southport","John Pugh","65354"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693727","Department for Education","false","2017-02-28","<p>Officials engage regularly with their counterparts in the devolved administrations on topics of mutual interest and concern. Addressing disadvantage was the topic of a recent four nations workshop facilitated by the British Council. It will also be a theme of the International Summit on the Teaching Profession to be co-hosted by the UK and Scottish Governments in March 2017, in partnership with the OECD and Education International, the global federation of teachers’ unions.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson",,"2017-02-28T17:04:42.227Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693727/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693727/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693727/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-02-23","Education: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, if she will hold discussions with her counterparts in (a) Scotland, (b) Wales and (c) Northern Ireland on how best to assist young people in socially deprived communities across the UK to obtain higher grades in core school subjects.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","65331"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693728","Department for Education","false","2017-03-02","<p>All nine standards that the Early Years Trailblazer was approved to develop in March 2014 remain in the development stage. We are committed to ensuring that all standards and assessment plans are developed in a timely manner so that they can be available to employers and apprentices to use. We have therefore notified the Trailblazer that we have withdrawn their right to develop these standards.</p><p> </p><p>We remain committed to supporting employers wishing to develop standards for use in the Early Years sector.</p><p> </p><p>The Children and Young People’s Workforce framework for England, at levels 2 and 3, remains in place which includes the Early Years Educator pathway, at level 3. This framework will remain in place until new early years standards are in place.</p>","Harlow","Robert Halfon",,"2017-03-02T17:25:39.233Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693728/answer","Biography information for Robert Halfon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693728/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693728/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-02-23","Apprentices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, whether the Early Years Apprenticeship Trail Blazer Group is still operational.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","65356"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693729","Department for Education","false","2017-03-04","<p>Young people with special educational needs and disabilities (SEND) are not automatically entitled to maintain their Education, Health and Care (EHC) plans after they turn 19. EHC plans are maintained beyond 19 where young people need special educational provision to meet the outcomes set out in their EHC plan. Those outcomes should focus on meeting the young person’s aspirations, and preparing them for adulthood.</p><p> </p><p>When a 19- to 25-year-old continues with an EHC plan, the local authority must review it at least annually. The plan must contain outcomes that should enable the young person to complete their education and training successfully and move on to the next stage of their lives. This will happen at different stages for individual young people, and EHC plans extended beyond age 19 will not all need to remain in place until age 25.</p><p> </p><p>For young people with more complex needs who are likely to continue to need specialist support in adult life, services will need to work together at a local level to plan and fund a smooth transition. These include children’s services, adult social care, housing and health.</p><p> </p><p>This strategic planning, aided by joint commissioning and integrated services, will support a young person to transition successfully to adult life, and receive the right support from adult services where needed.</p><p> </p><p>For students aged 19 and above who don’t have an EHC plan, <a href="https://www.gov.uk/discretionary-learner-support/overview" target="_blank">learner support funding</a> may be available to help them meet the additional needs of learners with learning difficulties and / or disabilities, and / or the costs of reasonable adjustments as set out in the Equality Act 2010.</p><p> </p><p>This support can cover a range of needs including:</p><ul><li>funding to pay for specialist equipment and helpers;</li><li>arranging note takers;</li><li>particular help in lectures and seminars; and</li><li>special arrangements for exams.</li></ul>","Harlow","Robert Halfon",,"2017-03-04T09:31:54.13Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693729/answer","Biography information for Robert Halfon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693729/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693729/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-02-23","Health Education: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, if she will make it her policy to give local authorities discretion in providing educational support to young adults over the age of 25 with an Education Health and Care Plan in the event that they have not received their full entitlement to support before their 25th birthday.","false","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","65293"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693730","Department for Education","false","2017-02-28","<p>The Government is making a huge investment in the school estate of £23 billion up to 2021, to create a further 600,000 new school places, deliver 500 new free schools, and rebuild and refurbish buildings at over 500 schools.</p><p> </p><p>From this, we are investing £10 billion in school replacement, maintenance and improvement works from 2016-2021. As part of this, the £4.4 billion Priority School Building Programme is rebuilding and refurbishing buildings in the very worst condition at more than 500 schools across the country.</p><p> </p><p>Under the first phase of the programme, building work is being undertaken at 260 schools. Of these, 177 schools have already opened in their new and refurbished buildings. The vast majority of schools within the first phase of the programme will be delivered by the end of 2017, two years earlier than originally planned.</p><p> </p><p>Since 2015, the Department has allocated funding on the basis of consistent condition data on the school estate, targeting funding where it is needed most. Funding is allocated each year to improve and maintain the condition of the school estate in order to address the condition need in the estate that was identified through the Property Data Survey.</p><p> </p><p>It is our aim that, over time, the condition need of the school estate will be addressed as more school buildings are replaced and refurbished.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-02-28T17:19:49.027Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693730/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693730/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693730/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-02-23","Schools: Buildings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what steps she is taking to ensure that all state school buildings are rated as being of a satisfactory standard; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","65260"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693731","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-03-03","<p>The Environment Agency has not put any flood prevention schemes in place in the Beckenham constituency since 2015. However between 2013 and 2015, the Government has invested £155,000 on capital works, better protecting 12 properties from flooding, and £450,000 on maintenance works along the River Ravensbourne.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Between April 2016 and March 2021, the Government plans to invest a further £924,000 on flood risk management schemes in the Beckenham constituency, better protecting around 200 properties from flooding.</p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-03-03T10:53:36.933Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693731/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693731/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693731/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-02-23","Flood Control: Beckenham","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how many flood prevention schemes have been put in place in Beckenham constituency since 2015.","false","Biography information for Bob Stewart","Beckenham","Bob Stewart","65244"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693732","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-02-28","<p>Our consultation on banning the use of microbeads in cosmetics and personal care products asks for evidence on the extent of the environmental impacts of microplastics, including microbeads, found in other products and processes. This includes whether microbeads are used in industrial processes and whether they end up in the marine environment. If they do we will use this information to inform future UK actions to protect the marine environment.</p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-02-28T11:51:59.153Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693732/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693732/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693732/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-02-23","Marine Environment: Microplastics","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what assessment she has made of the effect of microbeads used in industrial processes on marine wildlife.","false","Biography information for Sarah Olney","Richmond Park","Sarah Olney","65312"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693733","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-02-28","<p>We are currently running a consultation on our proposals to ban microbeads in cosmetics and personal care products. The consultation ends on 28th February 2017. The consultation also seeks to gather evidence on the extent of the environmental impacts of microplastics, including microbeads, found in other products. This evidence will be used to inform future UK actions to protect the marine environment.</p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-02-28T10:26:18.627Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693733/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693733/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693733/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-02-23","Microplastics","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what plans she has to tackle the use of microbeads in products outside the scope of her Department's proposed ban.","false","Biography information for Sarah Olney","Richmond Park","Sarah Olney","65313"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693734","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-02-28","<p>We are currently running a consultation on our proposals to ban microbeads in cosmetics and personal care products. The consultation ends on 28th February 2017. The consultation also seeks to gather evidence on the extent of the environmental impacts of microplastics, including microbeads, found in other products. This evidence will be used to inform future UK actions to protect the</p><p>marine environment.</p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-02-28T10:25:21.227Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693734/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693734/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693734/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-02-23","Microplastics","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, if she will make it her policy to extend the ban on microbeads to include non-cosmetic and non-domestic products.","false","Biography information for Sarah Olney","Richmond Park","Sarah Olney","65311"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693735","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-02-28","<p>The US ban has not yet come into force but we will continue to monitor its progress</p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-02-28T11:54:26.427Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693735/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693735/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693735/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-02-23","Microplastics: USA","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what assessment she has made of the effectiveness of the decision to ban microbeads by the US.","false","Biography information for Sarah Olney","Richmond Park","Sarah Olney","65314"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693736","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-03-01","<p>The Mayor is responsible for air quality in the capital and has reserve powers under Part IV of the 1995 Environment Act to enable this. Under the Act, the Mayor may direct the boroughs in the Greater London area concerning how they should assess and prioritise action in their areas. From September 2020 an Ultra-Low Emission Zone (ULEZ) will be introduced in London. The ULEZ will apply to all cars, motorcycles, vans, minibuses, buses, coaches and HGVs and will cover the same area as the current Congestion Charge Zone.</p><p> </p><p>The Government is firmly committed to improving the UK’s air quality and cutting harmful emissions. That is why we have committed more than £2 billion since 2011 to reduce transport emissions and the autumn statement provided a further £290 million to support greener transport. Air quality is improving, but the Government recognises that we need to go further and faster and we will be consulting on a new national plan by 24 April. The final plan will be in place by the end of July.</p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-03-01T13:10:21.763Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693736/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693736/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693736/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-02-23","Air Pollution: Greater London","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what steps she is taking to tackle high levels of air pollution in Greater London.","false","Biography information for Theresa Villiers","Chipping Barnet","Mrs Theresa Villiers","65282"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693737","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-03-01","<p>We are currently running a consultation on our proposals which end on 28th February 2017. The US ban has not yet come into force, but we will continue to monitor its progress and look to learn any lessons from its approach.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-03-01T13:07:17.677Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693737/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693737/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693737/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-02-23","Microplastics","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what steps she plans to take to ensure that the ban on the use of microbeads, announced by her Department on 3 September 2016, is comprehensive and effective; and if she will inform the House of the lessons learned from the ban on those products in the US.","false","Biography information for Mr David Anderson","Blaydon","Mr David Anderson","65281"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693738","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-02-28","<p>Defra officials have been in discussions with the US Food &amp; Drug Administration to help develop aspects of the UK approach on which we are currently consulting.</p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-02-28T12:04:08.887Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693738/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693738/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693738/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-02-23","Microplastics: USA","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, whether officials from her Department met counterparts from the Environmental Protection Agency in the US to discuss that country's ban on the production of personal care products and cosmetics which contain plastic microbeads.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","65353"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693739","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","true","2017-02-28","<p>Defra has not met with the World Health Organisation to discuss<ins class="ministerial"> microplastics</ins>.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-02-28T12:07:25.457Z","2017-02-28T17:36:33.457Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693739/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693739/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693739/answer","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693739/answer/previousversion/37453","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-02-23","Microplastics","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, whether officials from her Department have met officials from the World Health Organisation to discuss a ban on the use of microbead products.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","65358"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693740","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-02-28","<p>Yes.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-02-28T12:24:30.917Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693740/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693740/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693740/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-02-23","Microplastics: USA","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, if her Department will monitor the effectiveness of the US ban on microbeads which is due to come into effect in July 2017.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","65352"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693741","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-02-28","<p>Defra funded a study on micro plastics that was published last year and which has contributed to our knowledge base in formulating the consultation.</p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-02-28T15:33:15.14Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693741/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693741/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693741/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-02-23","Microplastics","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, if her Department will conduct an assessment of the potential biological effects of microbead products including those not in her Department's proposed ban.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","65332"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693742","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-02-28","<p>Since 2009 Defra has spent £15 million on oral badger vaccine development, using BCG (the attenuated strain of Mycobacterium bovis used worldwide to vaccinate people against TB). The Animal and Plant Health Agency has identified palatable bait and practical field deployment strategies. The immunity conferred by oral vaccination of badgers with BCG tends to be more variable than that resulting from the injectable formulation of the vaccine. Therefore, current studies are focusing on producing a safe, effective and affordable vaccine which provides consistent protection when eaten by badgers.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-02-28T09:40:50.633Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693742/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693742/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693742/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-02-23","Bovine Tuberculosis: Vaccination","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what steps her Department is taking to develop an oral M. Bovis vaccine for badgers; and what funding from the public purse has been made available for its development.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","65348"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693743","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-02-28","<p>BCG (the attenuated strain of Mycobacterium bovis used worldwide to vaccinate people against TB) remains the only viable option at present for vaccination of cattle against TB.</p><p> </p><p>The Animal and Plant Health Agency (formerly Animal Health and Veterinary Laboratory Agency) has shown a protective effect of BCG in cattle and developed delivery regimes for cattle. However, a DIVA test to differentiate vaccinated from infected animals must also be developed, as vaccination with BCG can interfere with the diagnostic tests routinely used to identify TB-infected cattle. APHA has developed such a test and further studies are ongoing to determine whether this will be suitable for use in the field. Once this has been determined, cattle vaccine field trials could be taken forward.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-02-28T09:44:16.907Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693743/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693743/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693743/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-02-23","Bovine Tuberculosis: Vaccination","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, which M. Bovis vaccines for bovine animals the Animal Health and Veterinary Laboratories Agency has access to for the purpose of trials; and what plans her Department has to run bovine vaccination trials.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","65349"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693744","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-02-28","<p>We are currently running a consultation on our proposals to ban microbeads in cosmetics and personal care products in preparation for the consultation which Defra carried out an assessment on the impacts of a ban. This concluded that a ban of this kind would help improve the state of the marine environment and address public concerns relating to consumer confidence in UK cosmetics. The impact on industry was considered to be low given that many companies had already committed to discontinuing their use.</p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-02-28T12:28:23.307Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693744/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693744/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693744/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-02-23","Microplastics","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, if she will make an assessment of the implications for her policies on the planned ban of microbeads.","false","Biography information for Anne Marie Morris","Newton Abbot","Anne Marie Morris","65429"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693745","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-03-02","<p>In terms of work arising from the UK’s vote to leave the EU, some 80% of Defra’s work is framed by EU legislation and a quarter of EU laws apply to Defra’s sectors.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Department has set up an EU Exit Programme led by a Director General to identify and coordinate work stemming from EU Exit across the Defra group. EU exit work is currently undertaken in all policy directorates in the Department, and in some corporate services areas. It is not possible to give an accurate figure of FTE civil servants working on the programme, given its extensive impact, nor to give a discrete figure regarding budget allocations to EU Exit.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-03-02T17:13:58.39Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693745/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693745/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693745/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-02-23","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what the terms of reference are for her Department's EU Exit Programme; how many full-time equivalent civil servants are working on that Programme; and what budget has been allocated to that Programme for each of the next two years.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","65432"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693746","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-03-03","<p>We are in close contact with the Malaysian authorities and stand ready to provide assistance if required.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-03-03T14:09:38.073Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693746/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693746/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693746/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-02-23","Kim Jong-nam","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what discussions he has had with his Malaysian counterpart on the killing of Kim Jong-nam.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","65410"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693747","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-03-03","<p>The Foreign Secretary, my Rt Hon. Friend the Member for Uxbridge and South Ruislip (Boris Johnson) has no contact with his counterpart.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-03-03T14:07:22.633Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693747/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693747/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693747/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-02-23","Kim Jong-nam","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what discussions he has had with his North Korean counterpart on the killing of Kim Jong-nam.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","65411"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693748","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-02-28","<p>When the Foreign Secretary, my Rt Hon. Friend the Member for Uxbridge and South Ruislip (Boris Johnson), visited Burma in January he raised a number of human rights concerns with both the civilian and military authorities. Specifically he called for a restrained security response in Rakhine State, for immediate humanitarian access there and for an end to discrimination against the Rohingya. He also called for a de-escalation of conflict in Kachin and Shan States, as well as for full humanitarian access. He did not specifically raise women's rights.</p><p>Protecting women's rights was, however, the explicit focus of the visit of the Minister of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, my noble Friend, the Rt Hon. the Baroness of Anelay of St Johns, who visited Burma in November in her capacity as the Prime Minister's Special Representative on Preventing Sexual Violence in Conflict. She used her visit to press the Minister of Defence on the importance of the army handling allegations of sexual violence against women in a thorough and transparent manner. She lobbied senior Ministers for a full and independent investigation into reports of human rights violations. During her visit the Minister heard direct from Rohingya leaders about the plight faced by their community in Rakhine State including a range of human rights violations. She also hosted a workshop in which she met survivors of sexual violence and practitioners engaged in efforts to prevent conflict-related sexual violence.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma","65426 ; 65427","2017-02-28T16:12:08.947Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693748/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693748/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693748/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-02-23","Burma: Females","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, whether he raised the issue of protecting women's rights with the Burmese Government on his recent visit to that country.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","65425"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693749","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-03-02","<p>​The reopening of our Embassy in Tehran in August 2015, and the subsequent upgrade in the relationship to Ambassadorial level in September 2016, provides us with the ability to discuss regularly a range of issues with the Iranian government, including regional affairs and to address areas including Iran’s policy towards Israel.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-03-02T15:09:13.097Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693749/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693749/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693749/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-02-23","Iran: Israel","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent discussions the Government has had with Iran on its policy towards Israel.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","65418"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693750","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-02-28","<p>When the Foreign Secretary, my Rt Hon. Friend the Member for Uxbridge and South Ruislip (Boris Johnson), visited Burma in January he raised a number of human rights concerns with both the civilian and military authorities. Specifically he called for a restrained security response in Rakhine State, for immediate humanitarian access there and for an end to discrimination against the Rohingya. He also called for a de-escalation of conflict in Kachin and Shan States, as well as for full humanitarian access. He did not specifically raise women's rights.</p><p>Protecting women's rights was, however, the explicit focus of the visit of the Minister of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, my noble Friend, the Rt Hon. the Baroness of Anelay of St Johns, who visited Burma in November in her capacity as the Prime Minister's Special Representative on Preventing Sexual Violence in Conflict. She used her visit to press the Minister of Defence on the importance of the army handling allegations of sexual violence against women in a thorough and transparent manner. She lobbied senior Ministers for a full and independent investigation into reports of human rights violations. During her visit the Minister heard direct from Rohingya leaders about the plight faced by their community in Rakhine State including a range of human rights violations. She also hosted a workshop in which she met survivors of sexual violence and practitioners engaged in efforts to prevent conflict-related sexual violence.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma","65425 ; 65427","2017-02-28T16:12:09.043Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693750/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693750/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693750/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-02-23","Burma: Females","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what representations he has made to his Burmese counterpart on protecting and promoting women's rights in that country in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","65426"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693751","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-02-28","<p>When the Foreign Secretary, my Rt Hon. Friend the Member for Uxbridge and South Ruislip (Boris Johnson), visited Burma in January he raised a number of human rights concerns with both the civilian and military authorities. Specifically he called for a restrained security response in Rakhine State, for immediate humanitarian access there and for an end to discrimination against the Rohingya. He also called for a de-escalation of conflict in Kachin and Shan States, as well as for full humanitarian access. He did not specifically raise women's rights.</p><p>Protecting women's rights was, however, the explicit focus of the visit of the Minister of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, my noble Friend, the Rt Hon. the Baroness of Anelay of St Johns, who visited Burma in November in her capacity as the Prime Minister's Special Representative on Preventing Sexual Violence in Conflict. She used her visit to press the Minister of Defence on the importance of the army handling allegations of sexual violence against women in a thorough and transparent manner. She lobbied senior Ministers for a full and independent investigation into reports of human rights violations. During her visit the Minister heard direct from Rohingya leaders about the plight faced by their community in Rakhine State including a range of human rights violations. She also hosted a workshop in which she met survivors of sexual violence and practitioners engaged in efforts to prevent conflict-related sexual violence.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma","65425 ; 65426","2017-02-28T16:12:09.107Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693751/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693751/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693751/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-02-23","Burma: Females","1",