"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693054","Department for International Development","false","2017-03-03","<p>As Rory Stewart, Minister of State for International Development set out at the report’s launch, the Government welcomes this report which assesses progress made during the first year of the Jordan Compact and considers what more needs to be done to create employment for refugees and the host community. The Government commends the significant progress made by Jordan and international partners during implementation of the Compact: almost 40,000 work permits have been issued to Syrians in Jordan, critical financing agreements have been signed with the World Bank and IMF, and a comprehensive trade deal was signed between the EU and Jordan at impressive speed. But we recognise that more needs to be done to improve the design and implementation of the Compact particularly by learning from refugees own work experiences and the issues faced by women in search of safe and decent work. The forthcoming Brussels Conference, which the UK will co-host, provides a key opportunity to increase momentum and ambition on delivery of the Jordan Compact.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2017-03-03T14:54:40.13Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693054/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693054/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693054/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-02-22","Syria: Refugees","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the recommendations in the report by the International Rescue Committee <i>In search of work: Creating Jobs for Syrian Refugees: A Case Study of the Jordan Compact</i>, published in February.","false","Biography information for Lord Hylton",,"Lord Hylton","HL5541"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693055","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-03-06","<p>As I set out in my written answer of 9 February (HL 5101) to the noble Lady, I have clarified the oral response I gave on 24 January (HL Deb, cols 547-9) regarding the Social Mobility Commission’s redefined statutory role. <br></p><p>This Government has an ambitious agenda for social reform, including taking firm action to tackle poverty and disadvantage. This work is being led by the new Social Reform Cabinet Committee, chaired by the Prime Minister, which has brought together nine Government departments to oversee and agree social policy reforms.</p><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Lord Henley",,"2017-03-06T15:35:44.553Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693055/answer","Biography information for Lord Henley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693055/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693055/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-02-22","Social Mobility Commission","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the letter from Lord Henley DEP 2017–0103, referred to in his Written Answer of 9 February (HL 5101), which stated that the Social Mobility Commission no longer has a statutory role in tackling child poverty, and to the answer by Lord Henley on 24 January (HL Deb, cols 547–9) which stated that "we have now set up something better—the Social Mobility Commission Secretariat" to fulfil the purpose of the Child Poverty Unit, how, and in what ways, the Commission will prove more effective than the Child Poverty Unit, and how it will provide the joined-up government approach to tackling child poverty as outlined in that answer.","false","Biography information for Baroness Lister of Burtersett",,"Baroness Lister of Burtersett","HL5542"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693056","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-03-07","<p>Homelessness is rarely just a housing issue. It is often the result of a combination of related issues including health, education, justice, welfare and employment.</p><p>That is why we are taking action across government, including through the Ministerial Working Group convened by DCLG, to make sure all departments are working together to tackle homelessness.</p><p>We are overhauling homelessness data to give us an even clearer understanding of the underlying causes and, most importantly, what really works to prevent and relieve homelessness.</p><p>We are investing over £500 million to tackle homelessness - including our £50 million Homelessness Prevention Programme - and we are supporting Bob Blackman's Homelessness Reduction Bill, to improve the support available for those facing a homelessness crisis and to ensure that people get help earlier to prevent their homelessness in the first place. Local authorities will be provided with £61 million of new burdens funding to carry out their new duties under the Bill.</p><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2017-03-07T17:21:54.093Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693056/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693056/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693056/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-02-22","Homelessness","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the key factors which have determined changes in the levels of homelessness in England and Wales since 2015.","false","Biography information for Baroness Lister of Burtersett",,"Baroness Lister of Burtersett","HL5543"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693057","Home Office","false","2017-02-28","<p>The Joint Council for the Welfare of Immigrants’ report includes findings about discrimination in relation to the Right to Rent scheme, but the Government’s view is that JCWI does not provide clear evidence that discrimination has arisen as a consequence of the scheme. However, the Government takes this issue seriously, and officials will meet with JCWI in order to discuss the findings in their report.</p><p> </p><p>The Government’s own evaluation of phase one of the scheme, in parts of the West Midlands, found no evidence of discrimination in terms of outcomes for prospective tenants.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2017-02-28T12:13:15.353Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693057/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693057/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693057/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-02-22","Undocumented Migrants: Private Rented Housing","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the findings of the Joint Council for the Welfare of Immigrants study of the impact of the right to rent checks on migrants and ethnic minorities in England.","false","Biography information for Baroness Lister of Burtersett",,"Baroness Lister of Burtersett","HL5544"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693058","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-03-02","<p>Non-executive members of the Channel 4 Corporation board are appointed by Ofcom with the approval of the Secretary of State. Ofcom advertised for four vacancies for candidates with specific sector skills and experience. The Secretary of State approved the four candidates on the basis that they met the skills and experience set out in the advertised job descriptions.</p>",,"Lord Ashton of Hyde",,"2017-03-02T16:39:51.707Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693058/answer","Biography information for Lord Ashton of Hyde","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693058/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693058/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-02-22","Channel Four Television: Public Appointments","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what consideration was given to the equality and diversity composition of the Channel 4 Board when the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport endorsed the appointment of four men to the Board and rejected the one female candidate who had also been recommended for appointment.","false","Biography information for Lord Ouseley",,"Lord Ouseley","HL5545"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693059","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-03-08","<p>The Cabinet Office Centre for Public Appointments, which works across Whitehall, as well as with the private sector and different stakeholder groups, has modernised recruitment practices and attracted a more diverse field of candidates from an ever-wider range of social and professional backgrounds by:</p><p> </p><p>· Placing an emphasis on ability, rather than prior experience, ensuring key roles in public bodies are open to those with skills required</p><p> </p><p>· Increasing awareness of public appointments through a central online advertising website, events and social media</p><p> </p><p>· Simplifying the application process to just require a CV and cover letter</p><p> </p><p>· Assessing every job advert to ensure they are fit for purpose and are open to a wider number of applicants to ensure a diverse pool of candidates.</p><p> </p><p>In 2013 the Government published its strategy for Increasing Diversity in Public Appointments. The Cabinet Office will be publishing an update to this strategy later this year.</p>",,"Baroness Buscombe",,"2017-03-08T12:13:22.55Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693059/answer","Biography information for Baroness Buscombe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693059/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693059/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-02-22","Public Appointments: Equality","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what policies and practices they advocate to encourage boardroom diversity and equality; what advice and encouragement they have given on diversity and equality to Channel 4; and to what effect.","false","Biography information for Lord Ouseley",,"Lord Ouseley","HL5546"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693060","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-03-02","<p>The government is committed to ensuring diversity within public appointments. The Cabinet Office aspiration is for 50% of new appointments made by each Government Department to go to female candidates, and 10% to candidates from a BAME background. This target is also contained within the DCMS Departmental Plan, and, in the first three quarters of 2016/17, 56% of new DCMS appointments went to women and 16% to BAME candidates.</p>",,"Lord Ashton of Hyde",,"2017-03-02T16:55:45.36Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693060/answer","Biography information for Lord Ashton of Hyde","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693060/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693060/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-02-22","Public Appointments: Equality","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what evidence they have to determine progress on the implementation of policies and practices to achieve diversity of representation on the boards of organisations supported by the Department for Culture, Media and Sport, with particular reference to black and minority ethnic women and disabled people's membership.","false","Biography information for Lord Ouseley",,"Lord Ouseley","HL5547"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693061","Home Office","false","2017-03-08","<p>Tackling knife crime is a priority for the Government. The Government’s Modern Crime Prevention Strategy published in March 2016 set out a range of measures to strengthen our response to knife crime. Since then we have delivered on our commitment to ban the sale, manufacture and importation of zombie knives and to extend our work with retailers to prevent the underage sale of knives.</p><p>We have agreed a set of commitments with major retailers to prevent the underage sales of knives more generally in their stores and online. The agreement also covers staff training and displays and packaging. Tesco, Lidl UK, Amazon UK, Wilko, Argos, Asda, Poundland, Morrisons, Sainsbury’s, John Lewis and Waitrose have all signed up to the principles. They have since been joined by Boots, the Co-op, B&amp;Q, Aldi and TKMaxx.</p><p>Raising awareness of the risks and consequences of carrying a knife is an important part of our knife crime prevention approach. We are working closely with organisations such as Redthread and St Giles, who intervene with young people at the “teachable moment”.</p><p>We also support Operation Sceptre, which are police led national coordinated weeks of action to tackle knife crime. In October 2016, 21 police forces across the country took part in the operation which included targeting habitual knife carriers, weapon sweeps, test purchases of knives from identified retailers, and the use of surrender bins. Further operations are being planned for 2017.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2017-03-08T12:14:32.133Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693061/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693061/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693061/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-02-22","Knives: Crime","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether any new initiatives are planned to deal with knife crime.","false","Biography information for Lord Ouseley",,"Lord Ouseley","HL5548"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693062","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-03-07","<p>Mr Miah was removed from a flight leaving Reykjavik. Officials have discussed Mr Miah's case with the US Embassy in London and the Ministry of Foreign Affairs in Iceland. The US authorities do not comment on individual cases but have confirmed the incident is not related to President Trump's January 27 Executive Order, which has in any case been suspended. We have provided Mr Miah with consular support and will continue to offer assistance to any British nationals that require it, but US immigration decisions are a matter for the US authorities.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2017-03-07T16:06:27.723Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693062/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693062/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693062/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-02-22","Juhel Miah","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what representations they have made to the US Embassy concerning the removal of Juhel Miah on a flight to the US; and what reason has been given for his removal.","false","Biography information for Lord Scriven",,"Lord Scriven","HL5549"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693063","HM Treasury","false","2017-03-07","<p>The latest tax gap figures published on 20 October 2016 in ‘Measuring Tax Gaps 2016' estimate the 2014-15 market share for illicit diesel in Northern Ireland as 8%. This amounts to about £50m in lost revenue. Petrol fraud is negligible.</p><p> </p><p>These estimates cannot be disaggregated by type of fraud such as smuggling or laundering.</p><p> </p><p>Figures for 2015-16 will not be available until autumn 2017.</p><p> </p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe","HL5551","2017-03-07T15:36:15.147Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693063/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693063/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693063/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-02-22","Fuels: Tax Evasion","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how much revenue was lost to HM Revenue and Customs due to (1) the smuggling of diesel oil from the Republic of Ireland, and (2) illegal fuel laundering within Northern Ireland, in financial year 2015–16.","false","Biography information for Lord Rogan",,"Lord Rogan","HL5550"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693064","HM Treasury","false","2017-03-07","<p>The latest tax gap figures published on 20 October 2016 in ‘Measuring Tax Gaps 2016' estimate the 2014-15 market share for illicit diesel in Northern Ireland as 8%. This amounts to about £50m in lost revenue. Petrol fraud is negligible.</p><p> </p><p>These estimates cannot be disaggregated by type of fraud such as smuggling or laundering.</p><p> </p><p>Figures for 2015-16 will not be available until autumn 2017.</p><p> </p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe","HL5550","2017-03-07T15:36:15.303Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693064/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693064/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693064/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-02-22","Fuels: Tax Evasion","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what percentage of the fuel market in Northern Ireland was made up of smuggled and fuel-laundered products in financial year 2015–16.","false","Biography information for Lord Rogan",,"Lord Rogan","HL5551"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693065","Department of Health","false","2017-02-28","<p>Wine sampling is conducted by the Government on a random and risk led basis. It therefore remains fully adaptable to respond to actual and perceived risks faced by the wine sector and consumers.</p>",,"Lord O'Shaughnessy",,"2017-02-28T16:59:23.68Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693065/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Shaughnessy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693065/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693065/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-02-22","Wines: Labelling","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord Gardiner of Kimble on 13 February (HL5188), whether the Food Standards Agency has identified any increased perceived risk of wrongly labelled French and Spanish wine in the light of widespread reports of wine fraud in the EU.","false","Biography information for Lord Blencathra",,"Lord Blencathra","HL5552"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693066","Department of Health","false","2017-02-28","<p>The Food Standards Agency (FSA) samples wine on risk basis and based on intelligence received from other Government departments or authorities in member states.</p><p> </p><p>The FSA takes two bottles of a particular wine during sampling exercises. The information of number of bottles sampled from European Union countries is shown in the following table.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Italy</p></td><td><p>Germany</p></td><td><p>United Kingdom</p></td><td><p>France</p></td><td><p>Spain</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>10</p></td><td><p>-</p></td><td><p>-</p></td><td><p>-</p></td><td><p>-</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>16</p></td><td><p>-</p></td><td><p>-</p></td><td><p>-</p></td><td><p>-</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>28</p></td><td><p>2</p></td><td><p>2</p></td><td><p>-</p></td><td><p>-</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p>100</p></td><td><p>-</p></td><td><p>12</p></td><td><p>2</p></td><td><p>4</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016</p></td><td><p>72</p></td><td><p>-</p></td><td><p>6</p></td><td><p>4</p></td><td><p>4</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Lord O'Shaughnessy",,"2017-02-28T16:57:38.057Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693066/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Shaughnessy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693066/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693066/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-02-22","Wines: Testing","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many bottles of wine were sampled by the Food Standards Agency from each EU country in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Lord Blencathra",,"Lord Blencathra","HL5553"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693067","Department of Health","false","2017-03-01","<p>The average number of patients per headcount general practitioner (GP) in England was 1,364 as at March 2016.</p><p> </p><p>Patients register with a practice, not an individual GP. There is no limit on the number of patients which a practice can have, but practices can close their list to new applications if they feel that they have insufficient resources to take on more patients.</p>",,"Lord O'Shaughnessy",,"2017-03-01T16:08:33.83Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693067/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Shaughnessy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693067/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693067/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-02-22","Doctors' List of Patients","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what is (1) the average number, and (2) the maximum permitted number, of patients per GP in England and Wales.","false","Biography information for Lord Blencathra",,"Lord Blencathra","HL5554"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693068","Department of Health","false","2017-03-01","<p>The Government is committed to improving access to general practitioner (GP) services, both during core hours and at evenings and weekends.</p><p> </p><p>The new GP contract means that surgeries which regularly close for mornings or afternoons on a week day will lose their eligibility for the current extended hours scheme claimed by most practices (through the Directed Enhanced Service). This change will come into effect from October 2017.</p><p> </p><p>By 2020/21, everyone will have access to routine GP appointments at evenings and weekends, investment in general practice will increase to £12 billion per year, and there will be an extra 5,000 doctors in working in general practice.</p>",,"Lord O'Shaughnessy",,"2017-03-01T16:09:03.907Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693068/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Shaughnessy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693068/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693068/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-02-22","GP Surgeries: Opening Hours","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they have any plans to make it compulsory for every GP surgery to be open from 8am to 6pm on Mondays to Fridays, and if so, whether they will reduce funding for those surgeries which do not comply.","false","Biography information for Lord Blencathra",,"Lord Blencathra","HL5555"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693069","Department for Education","false","2017-03-03","<p>The Government recognises that graduates play an important role in improving quality in the early years, and that is why in 2013 we introduced the early years initial teacher training programme which leads to the award of Early Years Teacher Status. We have made a significant investment in this programme by providing funding for course fees and bursaries to eligible trainees, and also funding for employers to support trainees.</p><p> </p><p>Research undertaken by Sandra Mathers and Rebecca Smee in 2014 showed that within the private, voluntary and independent sector, settings with a graduate member of staff scored more highly on all quality measures. Graduate leadership was also associated with a narrower quality gap between settings located in deprived and more advantaged areas. As such the Department supports and encourages those working in the sector to qualify as graduates if they so wish, but we do not currently have any requirements in place for staff working in the early years to be graduates.</p><p> </p><p>The forthcoming workforce strategy will set out the Government’s ambition for graduates in the early years in further detail.</p>",,"Lord Nash",,"2017-03-03T11:50:19.967Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693069/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693069/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693069/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-02-22","Pre-school Education: Teachers","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what is their response to the conclusions of a recent report by LSE and Surrey University that graduate nursery teachers for three- to five-year-olds make a small impact on children’s attainment compared to non-graduates; and whether they have any plans to review their policy regarding requirements for nursery staff to be graduates.","false","Biography information for Lord Blencathra",,"Lord Blencathra","HL5556"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693070","Department for Transport","false","2017-03-07","<p>There is not a requirement to modify all UK platforms to meet a height of 915 mm but if upgrade work is carried out this is currently the applicable height. For platforms on new railways, such as HS2, this height may be too low to facilitate level boarding and the application of alternative heights is being considered.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2017-03-07T13:18:23.467Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693070/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693070/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693070/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-02-22","Railway Stations","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon on 21 December 2016 (HL 4153), whether they plan to ensure that all new railway platform work will be carried out to the British specification of 915mm height in anticipation of leaving the EU; and what plans are being developed to bring all UK train platforms up to that standard.","false","Biography information for Lord Blencathra",,"Lord Blencathra","HL5557"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693071","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-03-06","<p>It is for individual local authorities to negotiate advertising rates with local newspapers. My department has not made a specific assessment of the cost to councils of publishing and issuing statutory notices but findings of the pilot programmes, including about costs, are being carefully considered.</p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","HL5559","2017-03-06T11:58:27.807Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693071/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693071/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693071/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-02-22","Local Government: Newspaper Press","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth on 9 February (HL5134), what assessment they have made of the cost of publishing and issuing statutory notices to councils and whether this will be included in their consideration of the findings of the pilot programmes.","true","Biography information for Lord Porter of Spalding",,"Lord Porter of Spalding","HL5558"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693072","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-03-06","<p>It is for individual local authorities to negotiate advertising rates with local newspapers. My department has not made a specific assessment of the cost to councils of publishing and issuing statutory notices but findings of the pilot programmes, including about costs, are being carefully considered.</p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","HL5558","2017-03-06T11:58:27.887Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693072/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693072/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693072/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-02-22","Local Government: Newspaper Press","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what steps they will take to ensure that local authorities which have only one local newspaper in their area for the purposes of publishing statutory notices will be protected from uncompetitive practices, such as high increases in the cost of publishing those notices.","true","Biography information for Lord Porter of Spalding",,"Lord Porter of Spalding","HL5559"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693073","HM Treasury","false","2017-03-07","<p>1 April 2015 is the point in time at which the rateable values are set, known as the antecedent valuation date. The new rating lists come into effect following revaluation after 1 April 2017.</p><p> </p><p>Official statistics were published on 6 October 2016 on the change in rateable values between the 2010 and 2017 rating lists following revaluation<sup> <sup>[1]</sup></sup>. These include the change in percentage terms of the total rateable value for England, Wales and each region of England (Table RV1.1) and for local authorities (Table 1.0).</p><p> </p><p>Valuation Office Agency data is not held in a way that easily allows data to be shown by parliamentary constituency.</p><p> </p><p>[1] <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/non-domestic-rating-change-in-rateable-value-of-rating-lists-england-and-wales-2017-revaluation" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/non-domestic-rating-change-in-rateable-value-of-rating-lists-england-and-wales-2017-revaluation</a></p><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2017-03-07T15:20:02.823Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693073/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693073/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693073/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-02-22","Non-domestic Rates","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what is their estimate of (1) the total rateable value of commercial property (a) before, and (b) after, the current revaluation as at 1 April 2015, and (2) the percentage change as a result of the revaluation, in (i) each local authority area, (ii) each parliamentary constituency, and (iii) each standard region in England and Wales.","false","Biography information for Lord Oakeshott of Seagrove Bay",,"Lord Oakeshott of Seagrove Bay","HL5560"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693074","Home Office","false","2017-02-28","<p>On 8 February, the Government announced that we will transfer the specified number of 350 children to the UK under section 67 of the Immigration Act following consultation with local authorities on capacity. We will announce in due course the basis on which further children will be transferred from Europe to the UK, where it is in their best interests, under section 67 of the Immigration Act to the specified number.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2017-02-28T12:14:37.233Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693074/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693074/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693074/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-02-22","Refugees: Children","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether admission to the UK of unaccompanied refugee children, under section 67 of the Immigration Act 2016, will start again in April 2017; and whether there will be limitations on entry, based on age, vulnerability, nationality or previous location.","false","Biography information for Lord Hylton",,"Lord Hylton","HL5561"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693135","Attorney General","false","2017-03-06","<p>It is not possible to be precise about the exact number of civil servants employed by the Law Officers' Departments who oversee contracts that have been awarded to external providers.</p>","South Swindon","Robert Buckland",,"2017-03-06T17:32:40.313Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693135/answer","Biography information for Robert Buckland","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693135/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693135/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2017-02-22","Attorney General: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, how many civil servants of the Law Officers' Departments oversee contracts which have been awarded to external providers.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","64992"
